    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start. My students might ask why this is different from 'procedural due process' though. Can you add a section explaining why substantive due process is the more important doctrine when it comes to actually securing rights for marginalized groups?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Procedural due process only requires the government to follow fair *procedures* when taking away a right, like providing a hearing. Substantive due process, however, goes further by questioning whether the *right itself* is being violated, regardless of how fairly the process was followed. For marginalized groups, substantive due process is vital because it allows courts to invalidate laws that are fundamentally unjust or infringe upon core liberties, even if the law was passed through the proper governmental channels. It is the doctrine that actively expands the scope of what the Constitution protects.",
      "source": "target",
